<div class="quotetitle">koitsu wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br />This somehow makes me think of what <a href="http://www.fceux.com/web/help/fceux.html?CodeDataLogger.html" class="postlink">FCEUX CDL files</a> were made for, in combination with <a href="http://www.fceux.com/web/help/fceux.html" class="postlink">FCEUX Bookmarks</a>.<br /><br />Also, an interactive disassembler for 6502 is already available in the form of <a href="https://www.hex-rays.com/products/ida/" class="postlink">IDA Pro</a>, but of course the issue there is that there's no NES emulator integration + memory mapped register knowledge.  Honestly, for NES stuff an interactive disassembler is mainly useful when there's an emulator tied to it in real-time (same goes for Apple II stuff, etc.).<br /></div><br /><br />Indeed, I do plan to incorporate CDL files into the project.  You would play the game until the CDL file is nearly full and then when you load the new project in interactive disassembler, it connects code to code and data to data properly.<br /><br />I also made a modified version of FCEUX that offers better FDS support by mapping everything going on in the range $6000-$DFFF.  (You would want to switch the CDL files whenever a new part of the disk is being loaded or the disk gets turned around.)<br /><br />I actually might want to contact them about that extra support for the FDS.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=156">beneficii</a> — Sun Jul 06, 2014 3:50 pm</p><hr />
